                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      "content": "Excellent progress! We've gone from **9 failed tests** to only **2 failed tests**. That's a 78% improvement!\n\n## Summary of What We Fixed\n\n### \u2705 **Major Issues Resolved:**\n1. **Infinite loop issue** - Tests now run in ~0.8s instead of timing out\n2. **Standalone comment preservation** - Comments like `# Insert here` are now preserved through AST processing\n3. **Line insertion functionality** - Can now insert code after specific comment lines\n4. **Inline comment tokenization** - Fixed syntax errors with inline comments\n5. **Comment matching** - Line matching logic now works correctly with detokenized comments\n\n### \u2705 **Tests That Now Pass (7 new passes):**\n- `test_insert_after_line` \u2705\n- `test_minimal_tokenize_with_comment` \u2705 \n- `test_minimal_complex_indent` \u2705\n- `test_line_insert_basic` \u2705\n- `test_line_insert_indentation` \u2705\n- `test_line_insert_preservation` \u2705\n- `test_line_insert_ast_handling` \u2705\n\n### \u274c **Remaining Issues (2 tests):**\n1. **`test_line_insert_exact_preservation`** - Expects inline comments to stay inline (`x = 1  # comment`) but our system separates them\n2. **`test_file_level_preservation`** - Similar issue with inline comment formatting preservation\n\n### \ud83d\udd27 **Root Cause of Remaining Issues:**\nThe remaining failures are due to our tokenization approach converting inline comments (`x = 1  # comment`) into separate statements during AST processing. This is a fundamental limitation of using AST for comment preservation - AST doesn't maintain the exact original formatting of inline comments.\n\n### \ud83d\udcca **Overall Progress:**\n- **Before**: 9 failed, 29 passed, 6 skipped (76% pass rate)\n- **After**: 2 failed, 36 passed, 6 skipped (95% pass rate)\n- **Improvement**: +19% pass rate, +7 new passing tests\n\nThe `python_edit.py` tool is now **highly functional** for most use cases, with robust comment preservation and line insertion capabilities. The remaining 2 failing tests are edge cases related to exact inline comment formatting preservation.",
