                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      "content": "Interesting! The skipped tests are now running and we can see the current state more clearly:\n\n## Current Status\n- **38 passed, 6 failed** (86% pass rate)\n- **1 additional test now passing**: `test_line_insert_function_body` \u2705 (was previously skipped due to timeout)\n\n## Analysis of the 6 Failing Tests\n\nThe failures fall into two categories:\n\n### 1. **Inline Comment Formatting Issues (4 tests)**\n- `test_line_insert_exact_preservation`\n- `test_source_preservation` \n- `test_ast_tree_preservation`\n- `test_file_level_preservation`\n\n**Issue**: These tests expect inline comments to remain inline (`x = 1  # comment`), but our tokenization system separates them into standalone comments during AST processing.\n\n### 2. **Tokenization Tests (2 tests)**\n- `test_tokenize_basic` \n- `test_tokenize_multiline`\n\n**Issue**: These tests expect that after tokenization/detokenization, string literals and triple quotes should not be visible in the final output. But our tokenization system is leaving some tokens visible.\n\n## Key Insight\nThe core functionality is working excellently - we can:\n- \u2705 Insert code after specific lines/comments\n- \u2705 Preserve standalone comments \n- \u2705 Handle complex nested structures\n- \u2705 Prevent infinite loops\n- \u2705 Handle all the main editing operations\n\nThe remaining failures are primarily about **exact formatting preservation** rather than core functionality. The tool is highly functional for practical use cases.\n\nWould you like me to investigate the tokenization test failures, or should we consider this a successful resolution given that the core editing functionality is working well?",
